{"questionId":"12588","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Olivia’s house consists of four vertical walls and a sloping roof made from two rectangles. The height, <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{CD}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>CD</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, from the ground to the base of the roof is 4.5 m.</p>\n<p>The base angles of the roof are <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{A}}\\mathop {\\text{B}}\\limits^ \\wedge&nbsp; {\\text{C}} = 27^\\circ \">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>A</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mover>\n    <mrow>\n      <mtext>B</mtext>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>∧</mo>\n  </mover>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>C</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <msup>\n    <mn>27</mn>\n    <mo>∘</mo>\n  </msup>\n</math></span> and <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{A}}\\mathop {\\text{C}}\\limits^ \\wedge&nbsp; {\\text{B}} = 26^\\circ \">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>A</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mover>\n    <mrow>\n      <mtext>C</mtext>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>∧</mo>\n  </mover>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>B</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <msup>\n    <mn>26</mn>\n    <mo>∘</mo>\n  </msup>\n</math></span>.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/11d726ebf724779378ad11ab96ea9ccddff3e9ce.png\"></p>\n<p>The&nbsp;house is 10 m long and 5 m wide.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Find the length <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{AB}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>AB</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span>, giving your answer to <strong>four significant figures</strong>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p style=\"color:#999;font-size:90%;font-style:italic;\">* This question is from an exam for a previous syllabus, and may contain minor differences in marking or structure.</p><p>180° − 27° − 26°&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong> (M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for correct working to find angle <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{B}}\\mathop {\\text{A}}\\limits^ \\wedge&nbsp; {\\text{C}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>B</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n  <mover>\n    <mrow>\n      <mtext>A</mtext>\n    </mrow>\n    <mo>∧</mo>\n  </mover>\n  <mo>⁡</mo>\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>C</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> or 127 seen.</p>\n<p><span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"\\frac{{{\\text{AB}}}}{{{\\text{sin}}\\,26^\\circ }} = \\frac{5}{{{\\text{sin}}\\,127^\\circ }}\">\n  <mfrac>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>AB</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n    </mrow>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>sin</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <msup>\n        <mn>26</mn>\n        <mo>∘</mo>\n      </msup>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n  <mo>=</mo>\n  <mfrac>\n    <mn>5</mn>\n    <mrow>\n      <mrow>\n        <mtext>sin</mtext>\n      </mrow>\n      <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace>\n      <msup>\n        <mn>127</mn>\n        <mo>∘</mo>\n      </msup>\n    </mrow>\n  </mfrac>\n</math></span>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em><em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for substitution into sine rule formula and <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em> for correct substitution.</p>\n<p>2.74450 (m)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p>(<span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{AB}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>AB</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> =) 2.745 (m)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)<em>(G4)</em></strong></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The final <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong> is for correctly rounding <strong>their</strong> unrounded <span class=\"mjpage\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" alttext=\"{\\text{AB}}\">\n  <mrow>\n    <mtext>AB</mtext>\n  </mrow>\n</math></span> to 4 sf. If 2.745 is given as the final answer, the unrounded answer need not be seen, award <em><strong>(M1)(M1)(A1)(A2)</strong></em>. For all other answers, the unrounded answer must be seen to an accuracy greater than 4 sf.</p>\n<p>Award <em><strong>(G3)</strong></em> for a final answer of 2.74450…(m) with no working. If radians are used then award at most <em><strong>(M1)(M1)(A1)(A0)</strong><strong>(A1)</strong></em><strong>(ft)</strong> for an answer of 3.920 (m).</p>\n<p><strong><em>[5 marks]</em></strong></p>","meta":{"questionId":"12588","referenceCode":"19M.2.SL.TZ1.T_2a","subjectId":"50-dp-mathematics-analysis-and-approaches","title":"Find the length AB , giving your answer to four significant figures.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"a","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 5]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","Prior learning","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, distance, midpoints","Topic 3— Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.2—2d and 3d trig, sine rule, cosine rule, area"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}